  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Federal Criminal Statutes:\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. State Statutes:\nMany states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws, with specific provisions tailored to state-level enforcement.\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish criminal penalties\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Create reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Impose civil and criminal sanctions for violations\n\nEnforcement is typically handled by federal agencies like:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\nThe laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
